    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>We use real-valued amplitudes for simplicity. The full Schrodinger equation uses complex amplitudes, and interference depends on relative phase. The particle-in-a-box is the simplest exactly solvable quantum system. Crowell builds up to the hydrogen atom (next chapter). Our probability amplitude example captures the essential logic: amplitudes add, then you square. This is the origin of all quantum weirdness.</p>

